## Why This Is Asked
Tests ability to reason about 128-bit data as four independent 32-bit lanes and perform lane-wise rotation without loops. Demonstrates precise bit-slicing, correct boundary handling, and minimal, provable code paths.

## Key Concepts
- 128-bit packing into 4×32 lanes
- Lane-wise rotation using (x<<n) | (x>>(32-n))
- Bit masking to confine intermediate results to 32-bit lanes
- Clamping n with & 31 to handle n >= 32

## Code Example
```c
typedef struct { uint64 lo; uint64 hi; } uint128;

uint128 rotateWithinLanes128(uint128 x, unsigned n) {
    n &= 31;
    uint32 a = (uint32)x.lo;
    uint32 b = (uint32)(x.lo >> 32);
    uint32 c = (uint32)x.hi;
    uint32 d = (uint32)(x.hi >> 32);

    a = n ? (a << n) | (a >> (32 - n)) : a;
    b = n ? (b << n) | (b >> (32 - n)) : b;
    c = n ? (c << n) | (c >> (32 - n)) : c;
    d = n ? (d << n) | (d >> (32 - n)) : d;

    x.lo = ((uint64)b << 32) | a;
    x.hi = ((uint64)d << 32) | c;
    return x;
}
```
